<p><b>Cecil John Rhodes</b> <a href="/wiki/Doctor_of_Civil_Law" title="Doctor of Civil Law">DCL</a> (5 July 1853 – 26 March 1902<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup>) was an <a href="/wiki/England" title="England">English</a>-born <a href="/wiki/Business" title="Business">businessman</a>, mining <a href="/wiki/Magnate" title="Magnate">magnate</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Politician" title="Politician">politician</a> in <a href="/wiki/South_Africa" title="South Africa">South Africa</a>. He was the founder of the diamond company <a href="/wiki/De_Beers" title="De Beers">De Beers</a>, which today markets 40% of the world's rough diamonds and at one time marketed 90%.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> He was an ardent believer in <a href="/wiki/Colonialism" title="Colonialism">colonialism</a> and <a href="/wiki/Imperialism" title="Imperialism">imperialism</a>, and was the founder of the state of <a href="/wiki/Rhodesia_(disambiguation)" title="Rhodesia (disambiguation)" class="mw-redirect">Rhodesia</a>, which was named after him. Rhodesia, later <a href="/wiki/Northern_Rhodesia" title="Northern Rhodesia">Northern</a> and <a href="/wiki/Southern_Rhodesia" title="Southern Rhodesia">Southern Rhodesia</a>, eventually became <a href="/wiki/Zambia" title="Zambia">Zambia</a> and <a href="/wiki/Zimbabwe" title="Zimbabwe">Zimbabwe</a> respectively. South Africa's <a href="/wiki/Rhodes_University" title="Rhodes University">Rhodes University</a> is named in tribute to him, and he is also known for the <a href="/wiki/Rhodes_Scholarship" title="Rhodes Scholarship">Rhodes Scholarship</a> which is funded by his estate.</p>
